---
import Layout from '../../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---
<Layout title="Binary Protocols">
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container learn-container">

      <nav class="breadcrumb">
        <a href="/learn">Learn</a>
        <span>›</span>
        <a href="/learn/protocols">Protocols</a>
        <span>›</span>
        <span>Binary Protocols</span>
      </nav>

      <div class="article-header">
        <span class="badge">Protocols · Article 5 of 5</span>
        <h1>Binary Protocols</h1>
        <p class="lead">
          NMEA gives you a position. Binary protocols give you everything the receiver knows —
          raw pseudoranges, carrier phases, Doppler, satellite health, internal filter states
          and hardware diagnostics. When you need raw measurements for RTK post-processing,
          PPP, or your own navigation algorithm, you need a binary protocol.
        </p>
        <div class="article-meta">
          <span>10 min read</span>
          <span>·</span>
          <span>Last updated March 2026</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="toc">
        <div class="toc-title">Contents</div>
        <ol>
          <li><a href="#why-binary">Why binary over NMEA?</a></li>
          <li><a href="#ubx">UBX — u-blox binary protocol</a></li>
          <li><a href="#sbf">SBF — Septentrio Binary Format</a></li>
          <li><a href="#binex">BINEX — Binary RINEX</a></li>
          <li><a href="#comparison">Protocol comparison</a></li>
          <li><a href="#converting">Converting to RINEX</a></li>
          <li><a href="#summary">Summary</a></li>
          <li><a href="#references">References</a></li>
        </ol>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 1 -->
      <h2 id="why-binary">Why binary over NMEA?</h2>
      <p>
        NMEA 0183 was designed in 1983 for single-channel GPS receivers outputting one position
        per second at 4800 baud. Modern GNSS receivers track 40+ satellites on multiple
        frequencies at up to 100 Hz. NMEA cannot carry this data volume efficiently — or at all
        in the case of raw measurements.
      </p>

      <div class="compare-table">
        <div class="ct-row ct-header">
          <span>Capability</span>
          <span>NMEA 0183</span>
          <span>Binary</span>
        </div>
        <div class="ct-row">
          <span>Raw pseudoranges</span>
          <span class="no">✗ Not available</span>
          <span class="yes">✓ Full precision</span>
        </div>
        <div class="ct-row">
          <span>Carrier phase measurements</span>
          <span class="no">✗ Not available</span>
          <span class="yes">✓ Millimetre resolution</span>
        </div>
        <div class="ct-row">
          <span>Doppler measurements</span>
          <span class="partial">~ VTG sentence (limited)</span>
          <span class="yes">✓ Per-satellite, full precision</span>
        </div>
        <div class="ct-row">
          <span>High update rates (&gt;5 Hz)</span>
          <span class="no">✗ Bandwidth limited</span>
          <span class="yes">✓ Up to 100 Hz</span>
        </div>
        <div class="ct-row">
          <span>Multi-constellation raw data</span>
          <span class="partial">~ Position only (GN talker)</span>
          <span class="yes">✓ Per-satellite, all constellations</span>
        </div>
        <div class="ct-row">
          <span>Internal filter states</span>
          <span class="no">✗ Not available</span>
          <span class="yes">✓ Kalman filter, ambiguity status</span>
        </div>
        <div class="ct-row">
          <span>Human readable</span>
          <span class="yes">✓ ASCII text</span>
          <span class="no">✗ Binary — needs parser</span>
        </div>
        <div class="ct-row">
          <span>Bandwidth efficiency</span>
          <span class="no">✗ ~8 bytes/character</span>
          <span class="yes">✓ ~2–3 bytes/value</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 2 -->
      <h2 id="ubx">UBX — u-blox binary protocol</h2>
      <p>
        UBX is the proprietary binary protocol developed by u-blox for their GNSS receiver
        modules. It is the most widely encountered binary protocol in the industry — u-blox
        chips are found in the vast majority of consumer devices, drones, IoT trackers and
        many professional survey receivers.
      </p>

      <h3>UBX frame structure</h3>
      <div class="frame-diagram">
        <div class="frame-byte">
          <div class="fb-label">Sync 1</div>
          <div class="fb-bits">1 byte</div>
          <div class="fb-val">0xB5</div>
          <div class="fb-desc">Always 0xB5 (µ in Latin-1). Marks start of frame.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="frame-byte">
          <div class="fb-label">Sync 2</div>
          <div class="fb-bits">1 byte</div>
          <div class="fb-val">0x62</div>
          <div class="fb-desc">Always 0x62 ('b'). Together with sync 1 = "µb" for u-blox.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="frame-byte frame-class">
          <div class="fb-label">Class</div>
          <div class="fb-bits">1 byte</div>
          <div class="fb-val">0x01–0x0D</div>
          <div class="fb-desc">Message class — groups related messages (NAV, RXM, CFG, MON, etc.)</div>
        </div>
        <div class="frame-byte frame-id">
          <div class="fb-label">ID</div>
          <div class="fb-bits">1 byte</div>
          <div class="fb-val">0x00–0xFF</div>
          <div class="fb-desc">Message ID within the class. Class+ID uniquely identifies the message type.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="frame-byte frame-len">
          <div class="fb-label">Length</div>
          <div class="fb-bits">2 bytes LE</div>
          <div class="fb-val">0–65535</div>
          <div class="fb-desc">Payload length in bytes, little-endian. Does not include header or checksum.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="frame-byte frame-payload">
          <div class="fb-label">Payload</div>
          <div class="fb-bits">variable</div>
          <div class="fb-val">message data</div>
          <div class="fb-desc">Message-specific data. All multi-byte integers are little-endian.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="frame-byte frame-crc">
          <div class="fb-label">CK_A, CK_B</div>
          <div class="fb-bits">2 bytes</div>
          <div class="fb-val">Fletcher-8</div>
          <div class="fb-desc">8-bit Fletcher checksum over class, ID, length and payload. Always validate.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3>Key UBX message classes</h3>
      <div class="msg-classes">
        <div class="mc-card">
          <div class="mc-class">NAV (0x01)</div>
          <div class="mc-desc">Navigation solution outputs — position, velocity, DOP, satellite info, time. These mirror NMEA but in binary with more detail.</div>
          <div class="mc-examples">NAV-PVT · NAV-SAT · NAV-DOP · NAV-STATUS · NAV-TIMEGPS</div>
        </div>
        <div class="mc-card mc-raw">
          <div class="mc-class">RXM (0x02)</div>
          <div class="mc-desc">Raw receiver measurements — the critical class for post-processing. Contains pseudoranges, carrier phases, Doppler and signal strength per satellite.</div>
          <div class="mc-examples">RXM-RAWX · RXM-SFRBX · RXM-MEASX</div>
        </div>
        <div class="mc-card">
          <div class="mc-class">CFG (0x06)</div>
          <div class="mc-desc">Configuration messages — enable/disable outputs, set update rates, configure ports, save settings to flash. Essential for receiver setup.</div>
          <div class="mc-examples">CFG-MSG · CFG-RATE · CFG-PRT · CFG-GNSS · CFG-SAVE</div>
        </div>
        <div class="mc-card">
          <div class="mc-class">MON (0x0A)</div>
          <div class="mc-desc">Monitoring — hardware status, communication port load, RF environment, firmware version. Useful for diagnostics and integration.</div>
          <div class="mc-examples">MON-HW · MON-RF · MON-VER · MON-COMMS</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="callout callout-info">
        <div class="callout-icon">🔑</div>
        <div>
          <strong>RXM-RAWX is the key message:</strong> For any post-processing, PPP or custom
          navigation application, enable <code>RXM-RAWX</code>. It contains pseudorange
          (metres), carrier phase (cycles), Doppler (Hz) and C/N₀ (dB-Hz) for every tracked
          signal at every epoch. This is the raw material for RINEX conversion and PPP processing.
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3>UBX checksum — Fletcher-8</h3>
      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">CK_A = 0; CK_B = 0</div>
        <div class="formula">for each byte b in [class, id, len_lo, len_hi, payload...]:</div>
        <div class="formula">    CK_A = (CK_A + b) & 0xFF</div>
        <div class="formula">    CK_B = (CK_B + CK_A) & 0xFF</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          The two checksum bytes are appended after the payload. Validate on every received frame —
          UBX on a UART at high baud rates can have framing errors.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 3 -->
      <h2 id="sbf">SBF — Septentrio Binary Format</h2>
      <p>
        SBF is Septentrio's native binary protocol, used across their entire receiver range —
        from the mosaic-X5 OEM module to the AsteRx survey receivers. Septentrio receivers
        are common in precision agriculture, surveying and scientific applications. SBF is
        notable for its completeness — it exposes more internal receiver state than most
        competing formats.
      </p>

      <h3>SBF frame structure</h3>
      <div class="sbf-frame">
        <div class="sbf-field">
          <div class="sbf-name">Sync</div>
          <div class="sbf-size">2 bytes</div>
          <div class="sbf-val">0x24 0x40 ("$@")</div>
          <div class="sbf-note">Fixed sync characters</div>
        </div>
        <div class="sbf-field">
          <div class="sbf-name">CRC</div>
          <div class="sbf-size">2 bytes</div>
          <div class="sbf-val">CRC-CCITT</div>
          <div class="sbf-note">Over ID, length and body. Placed before body — enables streaming validation.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="sbf-field sbf-key">
          <div class="sbf-name">ID</div>
          <div class="sbf-size">2 bytes</div>
          <div class="sbf-val">Block number + revision</div>
          <div class="sbf-note">Bits 0–12: block number. Bits 13–15: revision. Together identify message type and version.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="sbf-field">
          <div class="sbf-name">Length</div>
          <div class="sbf-size">2 bytes</div>
          <div class="sbf-val">8 – 65532</div>
          <div class="sbf-note">Total block length in bytes (multiple of 4). Includes header.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="sbf-field">
          <div class="sbf-name">TOW</div>
          <div class="sbf-size">4 bytes</div>
          <div class="sbf-val">ms since week</div>
          <div class="sbf-note">GPS Time of Week in milliseconds. 0xFFFFFFFF = not available.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="sbf-field">
          <div class="sbf-name">WNc</div>
          <div class="sbf-size">2 bytes</div>
          <div class="sbf-val">GPS week</div>
          <div class="sbf-note">GPS week number (continuous, no rollover). 0xFFFF = not available.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="sbf-field sbf-body">
          <div class="sbf-name">Body</div>
          <div class="sbf-size">variable</div>
          <div class="sbf-val">block data</div>
          <div class="sbf-note">Block-specific data fields. Padded to 4-byte boundary.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3>Key SBF blocks</h3>
      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Block number</th><th>Name</th><th>Content</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><strong>4006</strong></td><td>MeasEpoch</td><td>Raw code and phase measurements — the SBF equivalent of UBX RXM-RAWX. Essential for post-processing.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>4007</strong></td><td>MeasExtra</td><td>Extended measurement data — multipath estimates, smoothing corrections, channel tracking status.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>4001</strong></td><td>PVTCartesian</td><td>Position, velocity and time in ECEF. Includes accuracy estimates and solution type.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>4002</strong></td><td>PVTGeodetic</td><td>Position, velocity and time in geodetic coordinates (lat/lon/height).</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>5902</strong></td><td>BaseVectorCart</td><td>RTK baseline vector in ECEF. Includes ambiguity fix status and baseline accuracy.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>4012</strong></td><td>AttEuler</td><td>Attitude solution (heading, pitch, roll) for dual-antenna configurations.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>4095</strong></td><td>ReceiverStatus</td><td>Receiver health, tracking flags, RTC status, error flags. Essential for system monitoring.</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <div class="callout callout-info">
        <div class="callout-icon">🔧</div>
        <div>
          <strong>SBF advantage — MeasExtra:</strong> The MeasExtra block exposes per-channel
          multipath estimates, carrier-to-noise smoothing corrections and tracking loop bandwidth
          settings. This level of diagnostic detail is rarely available in competing formats and
          makes Septentrio receivers particularly useful for ionospheric research and signal
          quality analysis.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 4 -->
      <h2 id="binex">BINEX — Binary RINEX</h2>
      <p>
        BINEX (Binary RINEX) is an open, receiver-independent binary format developed by UNAVCO
        and adopted by IGS. Unlike UBX and SBF — which are proprietary to their manufacturers —
        BINEX is an open standard that any receiver vendor can implement and any software can
        parse without a licence.
      </p>
      <p>
        BINEX was designed to address RINEX's inefficiency for high-rate data. A 1 Hz RINEX
        file for a multi-constellation receiver is verbose — BINEX achieves 4–6× compression
        of the same data while remaining lossless. For 1 Hz CORS data archived over years,
        this compression matters.
      </p>

      <h3>BINEX frame structure</h3>
      <p>
        BINEX uses a flexible, self-describing format. Each record consists of:
      </p>

      <div class="binex-structure">
        <div class="bx-field bx-sync">
          <div class="bx-label">Sync byte</div>
          <div class="bx-val">0xC2 (little-endian) or 0xE2 (big-endian)</div>
          <div class="bx-note">Encodes byte order and CRC type in a single byte.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="bx-field">
          <div class="bx-label">Record ID</div>
          <div class="bx-val">1–4 bytes (UBNXI encoding)</div>
          <div class="bx-note">Variable-length unsigned integer. UBNXI uses fewer bytes for small IDs (most common case).</div>
        </div>
        <div class="bx-field">
          <div class="bx-label">Record length</div>
          <div class="bx-val">1–4 bytes (UBNXI encoding)</div>
          <div class="bx-note">Length of the record data in bytes.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="bx-field bx-key">
          <div class="bx-label">Record data</div>
          <div class="bx-val">variable</div>
          <div class="bx-note">Record-specific content. See BINEX ICD for record definitions.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="bx-field">
          <div class="bx-label">CRC</div>
          <div class="bx-val">1, 2 or 4 bytes</div>
          <div class="bx-note">CRC type indicated by sync byte. 1-byte XOR for small records, 4-byte CRC-32 for large.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3>Key BINEX record IDs</h3>
      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Record ID</th><th>Content</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><strong>0x00</strong></td><td>GNSS navigation records — ephemeris for GPS, GLONASS, Galileo, BeiDou</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>0x01</strong></td><td>GNSS metadata (site information, antenna, receiver)</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>0x7f</strong></td><td>Undifferenced GNSS observables — raw code, phase, Doppler per satellite. The BINEX equivalent of a RINEX observation epoch.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>0x7e</strong></td><td>Differential GNSS observables (single differences)</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>0x15</strong></td><td>Meteorological data</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <div class="callout callout-info">
        <div class="callout-icon">🌐</div>
        <div>
          <strong>Where you see BINEX:</strong> IGS archives store some real-time data in BINEX.
          UNAVCO distributes data from their network in BINEX. Several geodetic processing
          packages (TEQC, RTKLIB) can read BINEX directly. If you encounter a <code>.bnx</code>
          or <code>.binex</code> file, treat it like a binary RINEX observation file.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 5 -->
      <h2 id="comparison">Protocol comparison</h2>

      <div class="proto-compare">
        <div class="pc-row pc-header">
          <span></span>
          <span>UBX</span>
          <span>SBF</span>
          <span>BINEX</span>
        </div>
        <div class="pc-row">
          <span class="pc-factor">Manufacturer</span>
          <span>u-blox</span>
          <span>Septentrio</span>
          <span>Open (UNAVCO/IGS)</span>
        </div>
        <div class="pc-row">
          <span class="pc-factor">Open standard</span>
          <span class="no">No (public ICD)</span>
          <span class="no">No (public ICD)</span>
          <span class="yes">Yes — open standard</span>
        </div>
        <div class="pc-row">
          <span class="pc-factor">Raw measurements</span>
          <span class="yes">✓ RXM-RAWX</span>
          <span class="yes">✓ MeasEpoch</span>
          <span class="yes">✓ Record 0x7f</span>
        </div>
        <div class="pc-row">
          <span class="pc-factor">Max update rate</span>
          <span>25 Hz (F9P)</span>
          <span>100 Hz</span>
          <span>Receiver-dependent</span>
        </div>
        <div class="pc-row">
          <span class="pc-factor">Byte order</span>
          <span>Little-endian</span>
          <span>Little-endian</span>
          <span>Configurable (sync byte)</span>
        </div>
        <div class="pc-row">
          <span class="pc-factor">Checksum</span>
          <span>Fletcher-8 (2 bytes)</span>
          <span>CRC-CCITT (2 bytes)</span>
          <span>XOR / CRC-16 / CRC-32</span>
        </div>
        <div class="pc-row">
          <span class="pc-factor">RINEX converter</span>
          <span>RTKLIB, u-center</span>
          <span>sbf2rin (Septentrio)</span>
          <span>TEQC, RTKLIB</span>
        </div>
        <div class="pc-row">
          <span class="pc-factor">Primary use</span>
          <span>Consumer/pro u-blox receivers</span>
          <span>High-end geodetic/survey</span>
          <span>CORS archives, IGS RT</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 6 -->
      <h2 id="converting">Converting to RINEX</h2>
      <p>
        The standard workflow is to log raw binary data from the receiver, then convert to
        RINEX for post-processing, archiving or submission to correction services:
      </p>

      <div class="workflow">
        <div class="wf-step">
          <div class="wf-num">1</div>
          <div class="wf-content">
            <div class="wf-title">Enable raw output on receiver</div>
            <div class="wf-desc">UBX: enable RXM-RAWX and RXM-SFRBX (navigation data). SBF: enable MeasEpoch and GPSNav/GalNav blocks. Log to file at 1 Hz minimum.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="wf-step">
          <div class="wf-num">2</div>
          <div class="wf-content">
            <div class="wf-title">Log binary to file</div>
            <div class="wf-desc">RTKLIB str2str, u-blox u-center, Septentrio RxControl, or a custom serial logger. File size: ~1 MB/hour for a dual-frequency multi-constellation receiver at 1 Hz.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="wf-step">
          <div class="wf-num">3</div>
          <div class="wf-content">
            <div class="wf-title">Convert to RINEX</div>
            <div class="wf-desc">
              UBX → RINEX: <code>rtkconv</code> (RTKLIB GUI) or <code>convbin</code> (command line).<br/>
              SBF → RINEX: <code>sbf2rin</code> (Septentrio free tool).<br/>
              BINEX → RINEX: <code>teqc</code> or <code>gfzrnx</code>.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="wf-step">
          <div class="wf-num">4</div>
          <div class="wf-content">
            <div class="wf-title">Process or submit</div>
            <div class="wf-desc">Post-process the RINEX file with RTKPOST, submit to NRCan CSRS-PPP, or archive to a CORS data centre. RINEX 3.04 preferred for multi-constellation data.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Section complete -->
      <div class="section-complete">
        <div class="complete-icon">✅</div>
        <div>
          <div class="complete-title">Protocols section complete</div>
          <div class="complete-body">
            You now understand how GNSS data is formatted, transmitted and stored — from NMEA
            sentences on a serial port to binary raw measurements and RTCM correction streams.
            The next section covers the mathematics underpinning GNSS positioning engines.
          </div>
          <a href="/learn/mathematics" class="complete-link">Continue to Mathematics →</a>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 7 - SUMMARY -->
      <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2>
      <div class="summary-grid">
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">⚡</div>
          <div class="summary-title">Binary beats NMEA for raw data</div>
          <div class="summary-body">NMEA cannot carry pseudoranges, carrier phases or high-rate data. Binary protocols expose everything the receiver measures. No raw measurements = no post-processing or PPP.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">📡</div>
          <div class="summary-title">UBX — ubiquitous u-blox</div>
          <div class="summary-body">RXM-RAWX is the key message for raw data logging. Fletcher-8 checksum. Little-endian. Supported by RTKLIB and most open-source tools. Found in most drones, IoT and affordable survey receivers.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">🔬</div>
          <div class="summary-title">SBF — diagnostic depth</div>
          <div class="summary-body">MeasEpoch for raw data. MeasExtra exposes multipath estimates unique to Septentrio. CRC-CCITT checksum. sbf2rin for RINEX conversion. Used in precision agriculture and geodetic research.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">🌐</div>
          <div class="summary-title">BINEX — open standard</div>
          <div class="summary-body">Open format, receiver-independent. 4–6× more compact than RINEX. Used by IGS and UNAVCO for CORS data archiving. Record 0x7f carries raw observables. Parse with TEQC or RTKLIB.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="nav-footer">
        <a href="/learn/protocols/ntrip" class="nav-prev">← NTRIP</a>
        <a href="/learn/mathematics" class="nav-next">Mathematics →</a>
      </div>

      <div class="references" id="references">
        <h3>References and further reading</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>u-blox. <em>u-blox F9 HPG 1.32 Interface Description</em>. <a href="https://www.u-blox.com/en/docs/UBX-22008968" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">u-blox →</a></li>
          <li>Septentrio. <em>SBF Reference Guide v4.7</em>. <a href="https://www.septentrio.com/en/support/support-resources/documents" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Septentrio →</a></li>
          <li>Muellerschoen, R., Diggles, M., Touchtone, M. & MacLeod, L. (2004). BINEX: Binary Exchange Format. UNAVCO. <a href="https://binex.unavco.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">binex.unavco.org →</a></li>
          <li>RTKLIB v2.4.3 — open source GNSS processing software. <a href="https://rtklib.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">rtklib.com →</a></li>
        </ul>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>

